Find data:

Find two (!) datasets with one variable in common (e.g., dates, times, states, counties, countries, sports players), both with at least 50 observations (i.e., rows) in each. Please think very carefully about whether it makes sense to combine your datasets! If you find one dataset with 50 patients and it has their age, and you find another dataset with 50 different patients that has their ages, it makes no sense to join them based on age (you would just be pairing up random people of the same age).

When combined, the resulting/final dataset must have at least 4 different variables (at least 3 numeric) in addition to the common variable (i.e., five variables total).

You can have as many variables as you would like! If you found two datasets that you like but they dont have enough variables, find a third dataset with the same common variable and join all three.

Guidelines

  1. If the datasets are not tidy, you will need to reshape them so that every observation has its own row and every variable its own column. If the datasets are both already tidy, you will make them untidy with pivot_wider()/spread() and then tidy them again with pivot_longer/gather() to demonstrate your use of the functions. Its fine to wait until you have your descriptives to use these functions (e.g., you might want to pivot_wider() to rearrange the data to make your descriptive statistics easier to look at); its fine long as you use them at least once!

Rubric

Prerequisite: Finding appropriate data from at least two sources per the instructions above: Failure to do this will result in a 0! You will submit a .Rmd file and a knitted document (html/pdf).

0. Introduction (5 pts)

  • Write a narrative introductory paragraph or two describing the datasets you have chosen, the variables they contain, how they were acquired, and why they are interesting to you. Expand on potential associations you may expect, if any.

This project explores the global relationship between alcohol consumption and happiness. I found two datasets that contained a common variable of country and was able to use them for the project. The dataset on drinking contains information on the average consumption per citizen in each country. It examines wine servings, spirit servings, beer servings, total liters, and continent.The dataset on happiness includes each country with a happiness score, GDP per gapita, generosity, perceptions of corruption, healthy life expectancy, social support, and freedom to make life choices.

We are all familiar with the fact that alcohol is a depressant, but I was curious as to what exactly that meant for overall happiness. My underlying question was simply: does drinking more mean you will be a less happy person? There are countries that frequently score high on a happiness scale like Denmark and Finland, and I was curious if countries like this drink more while unhappy countries drink less. Because alcohol is a depressant, its reasonable to think that there would be a negative association between the two. I actually expected to find the opposite. While alcohol itself has negative impacts on your brains ability to feel happy, my instincts told me that countries where drinking is more pervasive might have wealthier citizens, more free time or leisure, more social interaction, etc. For this reason, I expected a positive relationship between alcohol consumption and the happiness score of each country.

1. Tidying: Rearranging Wide/Long (10 pts)

  • Tidy the datasets (using the tidyr functions pivot_longer/gather and/or pivot_wider/spread)
  • If you data sets are already tidy, be sure to use those functions somewhere else in your project (e.g., for rearranging summary statistics)

  • Document the process (describe in words what was done)

    Both of these datasets were already quite tidy. Each row had a value in each column, the countries in each respective dataset appeared only once, and the columns werent repetitive. I used pivot wider on both preliminary datasets, changing country to a column instead. This resulted in 150+ additional columns under the formal name of each country with the happiness score or the total liters of alcohol consumed as its value, depending on which dataset I was altering. I then used pivot longer to reverse this change and resume examination of the tidy datasets.

2. Joining/Merging (10 pts)

  • Join your datasets into one using a dplyr join function
  • If you have multiple observations on the joining variable in either dataset, fix this by collapsing via summarize
  • Discuss the process in words, including why you chose the join you did
  • Discuss which cases were dropped, if any, and potential problems with this

I decided to do a full join of these two datasets. I first renamed the country column in the happiness dataset, then full joined the two. There were no repeated observations, so it was not necessary to fix by collapsing with summarize. I could several other types of joins using just the specific identifier and columns I wanted, but the data overlapped quite nicely and I wanted to retain the IDs and information associated. There were a hand full of countries that were dropped, most likely due to different naming processes. For example, the United States could be referred to as such, or by USA. There are problems with lost data in the case of countries; to fully examine the happiness of countries compared to their alcohol consumption, a project would ideally examine the entire population of countries rather than a sample subset containing less than the full number. With 156, I felt I gained ample insight into the relationship of these two identifiers and upheld a robust dataset.

    • If applicable, at least 1 of these should group by two categorical variables

To mutate the data frame, I created a new column called Total Servings, which was the sum of the servings for wine, beer, and spirits. I thought this was an easier way to look at the total consumption of alcohol compared to liters, because the consumption of a liter of beer is so different from a liter of spirits or wine etc. I also used the subset function to remove several variables that I felt were not relevant. I used several dplyr functions to just visualize the data in a different way. For example, I used filter to look at it through the lens of each continent, one by one. I then calculated the mean of each numeric variable, the sd, the min, the max, the distinct data points, etc. before doing these calculations again with the data grouped by continent. I thought continent would be a better way to group than by country because each country was its own unique occurrence. It was interesting to compare the values from grouped and ungrouped data, specifically the means of servings. This inspired me to explore the relationship between continent and drinking later in the project. This categorical variable made it easy to group and examine.

4. Visualizing (30 pts)

  • Create a correlation heatmap of your numeric variables the way we did in class

  • Create two more effective, polished plots with ggplot

    • Each plot should map 3+ variables to aesthetics
    • Each plot should have a title and clean labeling for all mappings
    • Change at least one default theme element and color for at least one mapping per plot
    • For at least one plot, add more tick marks (x, y, or both) than are given by default
    • For at least one plot, use the stat=summary function
    • Supporting paragraph or two (for each plot) describing the relationships/trends that are apparent

This correlation plot explored the relationship between each of the variables of my tidied, merged dataset. Higher correlation is shown in red, while lower correlation is shown in blue. Because many of my numeric variables looked at the breakdown of alcohol consumption, there was fairly high correlation between many variables. For example, a country with a higher total alcohol servings value will likely have a higher beer, wine, and spirits serving too. For this reason, theres a lot of red showing up on the correlation plot. The highest correlations are seen between total liters of alcohol and total servings. This makes a lot of sense; more liters of alcohol means more alcohol being consumed in general. Its unlikely for that to mean the average person is consuming way above average in, say, wine and way below average in another type of alcohol, so it makes sense that these two variables would have a high correlation. The lowest correlation is seen between the happiness score and overall rank. A high happiness score means a lower overall rank because the values are descending. This correlation plot is a little disappointing just because the majority of the striking information comes on semantics as I have discussed above. That being said, I found it interesting that the more neutral correlations, or the most lacking correlations are seen in perceptions of corruption. There was very little relationship between the perceptions of corruption and the total servings, total liters, and beer servings. I had debated removing this variable since it didnt completely align with the questions I had on alcohol as a depressant, but I found it very interesting so I kept it. This correlation plot made me glad I did!

The second plot I created was examining the central question of my project. It explores the relationship between happiness score and total alcohol servings, and finds a slight positive association. The line of best fit finds a positive, linear seeming relationship between the total servings and the happiness score. I colored each point by the continent that country belongs to. From what I can tell, theres not a huge relationship here. It looks like some of the countries with higher servings seem to be green, indicating Europe, but there are some values on the lower side here as well. It does look like African and South American countries cluster toward the lower side of alcohol servings. I included additional tick marks on the x-axis here to better show the number of servings associated with the point.

I was inspired to explore the perceptions of corruption variable a bit more. I wanted to see if perceptions of corruption raise or lower as a function of total alcohol servings, so I plotted these variables and used geom_smooth. While the line is satisfying to look at, there doesnt seem to be a huge relationship here either. The highest serving countries do, however, seem to have the highest perceptions of corruption as well. Its not apparent from the graph if this relationship is significant, but it would be interesting to look more into the relationship these two variables have.

The final plot I decided to do was looking at total servings by continent. This graph used stat=summary, meaning the mean for each continent was used. The results on this one were by far the most interesting to look at. Adding error bars confirmed my suspicion that there were major differences between the total servings by continent. Africa and Asia were the lowest by a significant amount, while Europe and Oceania were the highest. North and South America fell more in the middle.

5. Dimensionality Reduction (30 pts)

  • Either k-means/PAM clustering or PCA (inclusive or) should be performed on at least three of your variables (3 is just the minimum: using more/all of them will make this much more interesting!)

    • All relevant steps discussed in class (e.g., picking number of PCs/clusters)
    • A visualization of the clusters or the first few principal components (using ggplot2)
    • Supporting paragraph or two describing results found, interpreting the clusters/PCs in terms of the original variables and observations, discussing goodness of fit or variance explained, etc.

We use k-means to sort the data into k clusters on the basis of their stats variables. The centers are moved to the middle of each cloud of points; this adjustment changes them to centroids. We repeat this until the groups stabilize. We take each cluster and recompute the center for each one, representing the mean of x and mean of y for each one. Then we reassign the points to whichever centroid they are closest to.

Weighting the variables wasnt applicable because each numeric that I examined versus the happiness score was in the scale of servings, so they were already weighted, in a sense. I performed a k-means clustering with beer servings and score, wine servings and score, and spirit servings and score. The first step was to create cluster data using dplyr to select for the two variables I was interested in. I then applied kmeans to the clustered data by looking at the number of groups there appeared to me. I looked at the between differences and within differences of the kmeans before mutating as a factor of the cluster. I then plotted with ggplot and geom_point to visualize which datapoints had been assigned to which cluster. My hope was to look at the cluster data and see that different continents were assigned to different clusters. After the data visualization showed me that continents were significant in their differences of total servings, I had hoped that this would make itself known in the clusters as well. However, I did not notice this pattern in the data or the visualizations, so I selected the cluster values based on the rough estimate of number of clusters I saw. The clusters were selected using WSS and BSS with the silhouette width. Higher silhouette width is better, so a value of 10 was satisfying to me.
